[[File:In the Heart of the Beast Puppet and Mask Theatre.jpg|thumb|Theatre entrance and [[marquee (sign)|marquee]].]] '''In the Heart of the Beast Puppet and Mask Theatre''' (also known as '''Heart of the Beast''' or '''HOBT''') is a [[puppeteer|puppet company]] and [[nonprofit organization]] from [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.propelnonprofits.org/studies/heart-beast-puppet-mask-theatre/ |title=In the Heart of the Beast Puppet and Mask Theatre |publisher=Propel Nonprofits |accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> The company has written and performed scores of full-length puppet plays, performed throughout the US, [[Canada]], [[Korea]], and [[Haiti]] and toured the [[Mississippi River]] from end to end. The theatre is best known for sponsoring the annual [[May Day]] [[Parade]] and [[Ceremony]] that is seen by as many as 50,000 people each year.<ref name=AAPress>{{cite web |url=http://aapress.com/community/44th-mayday-parade-ceremony-festival-set-by-heart-of-the-beast-puppet-and-mask-theatre/ |title=44th MayDay Parade, Ceremony & Festival set by Heart of the Beast Puppet and Mask Theatre |publisher=Asian American Press |date=April 13, 2018 |accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.startribune.com/family-fun-in-the-heart-of-the-beast-may-day-prep/478889723/ |title=Family fun: In the Heart of the Beast May Day prep |author=Melissa Walker |date=April 5, 2018 |publisher=Star Tribune |accessdate=July 16, 2018}} {{subscription required}}</ref>
== History == HOBT began in 1973 as '''Powderhorn Puppet Theatre''', named for a neighborhood park and lake in Minneapolis.<ref>{{cite url|url=https://hobt.org/about/ |title=About Us |publisher=In the Heart of the Beast Puppet and Mask Theatre |accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref> In 1975, the theatre organized their first May Day procession and event.<ref name=ToW>{{cite book |title=Theatre of Wonder: 25 Years in the Heart of the Beast |year= 1999 |editor-first=Colleen J. |editor-last=Sheehy |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |isbn=978-0816634200 |url=https://www.upress.umn.edu/book-division/books/theatre-of-wonder }}</ref>{{rp|50-51}} About 50-60 people and a few puppets marched, raised a [[maypole]] in the park, and had some speeches. In the next years, the event grew and evolved into a way to celebrate community builders.<ref name=ToW />{{rp|51}}
In 1979, the theatre changed its name<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hobt.org/about/our-name/ |title=About Our Name |publisher=In the Heart of the Beast Puppet and Mask Theatre |accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref> based on a suggestion by poet and theatre member Steven Lisner.<ref name=ToW />{{rp|45}} In 1987, they moved into the Avalon Theater, a former [[Movie theater|cinema]] originally built in 1909 as the Royal Theatre.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cinematreasures.org/theaters/5331 |title=Avalon Theater in Minneapolis, MN |author=Sean Ryan |publisher=Cinema Treasures |accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref> HOBT purchased the Avalon Theater in 1990 for the building and staging of productions.
In 1999, the [[Weisman Art Museum]] at the [[University of Minnesota]] exhibited ''Theatre of Wonder: Twenty-five Years In the Heart of the Beast'', celebrating the works and productions by the theatre.<ref name=ToW />{{rp|1}}
In 2017, the theatre received $275,000 from the will of Sarah Bowman, a performer and longtime supporter of the theatre. The funds are planned to be used in upgrading the theatre building.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.twincities.com/2017/08/07/late-heart-of-the-beast-theater-supporterperformers-gift-will-fund-big-things/ |title=Late Heart of the Beast theater supporter/performer's gift will fund big things |author=Chris Hewitt |publisher=Pioneer Press |date=August 7, 2017 |accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, the organization was awarded a grant by [[The Jerome Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twincitiesarts.com/2018/06/15/news-jerome-foundation-announces-inaugural-organization-grant-recipients/ |title=NEWS: Jerome Foundation Announces Inaugural Organization Grant Recipients |author=Basil Considine |date=June 15, 2018 |publisher=Twin Cities Arts Reader |accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref>
== Productions == Over the years, productions have used various styles of puppet and mask performances, including ''[[bunraku]]'' and larger-than-life puppets.<ref name=ToW />{{rp|11-12}} These include:<ref name=ToW />{{rp|102-131}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hobt.org/performances/ |title=Main Stage Productions |publisher=In the Heart of the Beast Puppet and Mask Theatre |accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> * "Puppet Cabaret!" (quarterly) * "The Minotaur or: Amelia Earhart is Alive and Traveling in the Underworld" (2018)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lavendermagazine.com/featured-home-page/flying-sorcery-a-stirringly-mythical-the-minotaur-or-amelia-earhart-is-alive-and-traveling-in-the-underworld/ |title=Flying Sorcery – A Stirringly Mythical 'The Minotaur or: Amelia Earhart is Alive and Traveling in the Underworld' |author=John Townsend |date=June 19, 2018 |publisher=[[Lavender (magazine)|''Lavendar'']] |accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> * "Make Believe Neighborhood", celebrating [[Mr. Rogers]] (2018)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.startribune.com/heart-of-the-beast-puppet-theater-invites-you-to-mr-rogers-neighborhood/472182683/ |title=Heart of the Beast puppet theater invites you to Mr. Rogers' neighborhood |author=Chris Hewitt |publisher=Star Tribune |date=February 2, 2018 |accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> * [[Nativity of Jesus|"La Natividad"]] (2016, 2014, 2012, 2008, 2007, 2006) * "Crow Boy", based on the children's book by [[Taro Yashima]] (2016)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2016/02/17/heart-beast-theatre-crow-boy-minneapolis |title=At Heart of the Beast, a children's book grows up |author=Euan Kerr |date=February 17, 2016 |publisher=[[MPR News]] |accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> * "[[La Befana]]" (2010, 2001, 1995, 1991, 1989, 1988, 1984, 1983, 1982, 1981, 1979, 1974) * "The Story of [[Iqbal Masih]]" (1997) * "''[[Don Quixote]]''" (1994, 1993) * "This Land", a tribute to [[Woody Guthrie]] (1993) * "''[[Beowulf]]''" (1985) * "[[The Fisherman and His Wife]]" (1975, 1974)
== May Day Parade and Tree of Life Ceremony == [[File:Minneapolis May Day Tree of Life Ceremony 2018.jpg|thumb|left|Larger-than-life puppet held up by numerous volunteers at the 2018 Tree of Life Ceremony.]] [[Image:Sky and Prairie-Powderhorn-Minneapolis-2006-05-07.jpg|thumb|right|HOBT May Day Tree of Life Ceremony in [[Powderhorn Park]].]] The annual parade hosted by In the Heart of the Beast Theatre draws large crowds and showcases large puppets and floats and entertainment by performers.<ref>{{cite news |title=In the Heart of the Beast Theatre's MayDay Parade |newspaper=[[Star Tribune]] |author=Xavier Wang |date=May 9, 2017 |url=http://www.startribune.com/in-the-heart-of-the-beast-theatre-s-mayday-parade/421561533/ |accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref> Each year's parade/festival has a theme, ranging from Spring and environmental topics to social topics like peace and racial justice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sandyspieler.com/years-of-mayday/ |title=The Themes of the 41 Years of MayDay! |author=Sandy Spieler |accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> The event also features a festival in [[Powderhorn Park]] and a Tree of Life Ceremony involving more than 300 performers.<ref name=AAPress /> {{clear}} === May Day Parade gallery === <gallery> Image:May Day Parade -1-Minneapolis-2007-05-06.jpg Image:MayDay Parade, Minneapolis (15676505307).jpg Image:May_Day_Parade-2-_2007-05-06.jpg Image:May Day Parade-Minneapolis-20070506.jpg Image:MayDay Parade, Minneapolis (15676131569).jpg Image:MayDay Parade, Minneapolis (15676376587).jpg Image:MayDay Parade, Minneapolis (15675014220).jpg Image:MayDay Parade, Minneapolis (15676380847).jpg Image:MayDay Parade, Minneapolis (15862292995).jpg Image:MayDay Parade, Minneapolis (15860142701).jpg Image:MayDay Parade, Minneapolis (15860151061).jpg Image:Minneapolis May Day Parade 15860321641.jpg Image:Minneapolis May Day Parade — Tuba Bike 4572548265 o.jpg Image:Minneapolis May Day Parade 2018 -- We Feed You Love float.jpg </gallery>
