{{Multiple issues|{{cleanup|date=February 2015|reason=Location information and general proofreading}}{{tone|date=February 2015}}}}{{Infobox monument|complete=|begin={{start date|df=y|1990|12|5}}|caption=Monjaya Statue|coordinates={{coord|7|11|43.6|S|112|44|22.4|E|}}|dedicated_to=[[Indonesian Navy]]|designer=[[:id:I Nyoman Nuarta|I Nyoman Nuarta]]|extra=|height={{Plainlist |
* Statue: {{Convert|30.6|m|ft}}
* Including base: {{Convert|60.6|m|ft}}}}|image=File:Jalesveva Jayamahe statue photo.jpg|location=[[Port of Tanjung Perak]], [[Surabaya]], Indonesia|map_caption=Location of Jalesveva Jayamahe|map_width=|monument_name=Jalesveva Jayamahe Monument|open={{end date and age|df=y|1996|12|5}}|width=|type=[[Statue]]|map_name=Indonesia_Surabaya#Indonesia Java#Indonesia|website=[https://sparkling.surabaya.go.id/jalesveva-jayamahe/ Jalesveva Jayamahe]|native_name=''Monjaya''}}

'''Jalesveva Jayamahe Monument''' or can be locally referred to as '''Monjaya''' is a Statue of an [[Indonesian Navy]] officer wearing Ceremonial Service Dress, complete with his sword of honor, staring far to the sea as if he's ready to challenge the ocean's tide and storms. It represents the preparedness of the Indonesian Navy for glory. The statue is standing tall above a building, the total height of the building and the statue reaches 60.6 meters (approximately 198 feet and 9 inches).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sparkling.surabaya.go.id/jalesveva-jayamahe/|title=Jalesveva Jayamahe {{!}} Dinas Kebudayaan dan Pariwisata Kota Surabaya|website=sparkling.surabaya.go.id|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-25}}</ref> Jalesveva Jayamahe Monument representing the nation's future generation's optimism towards the accomplishment of Indonesian dream.<ref>''[http://monumenjalesvevajayamahe.blogspot.com/p/blog-page_13.html Travelling to Jalesveva Jayamahe Monument {{flagicon|Indonesia}}][[Indonesia|[[File:Flag_of_Indonesia.svg|link=|alt=Indonesia|23x23px]]]][[Indonesia|[[File:Flag_of_Indonesia.svg|link=|alt=Indonesia|23x23px]][[File:Flag_of_Indonesia.svg|link=|alt=Indonesia|23x23px]][[File:Flag_of_Indonesia.svg|link=|alt=Indonesia|23x23px]][[File:Flag_of_Indonesia.svg|link=|alt=Indonesia|23x23px]][[File:Flag_of_Indonesia.svg|link=|alt=Indonesia|23x23px]]]]''</ref>

The monument's name is taken from Indonesian Navy's motto in [[Sanskrit]] ''Jalesveva Jayamahe'' which means ''Our Glory is at the Seas''. The construction started in 1993 by Indonesian Chief of Naval, later continued by [[Indonesian National Armed Forces|Indonesian National Force]] [[Admiral]] Muhammad Arifin and designed by I Nyoman Nuarta. Other than as a monument, this building is also functioning as a lighthouse for ships or vessels at surrounding sea.<ref>''[http://www.eastjava.com/tourism/surabaya/jalesveva.html Monument of Jalesveva Jayamahe]'', by Surabaya Tourism</ref><ref>''[http://www.tnial.mil.id/News/Seremonial/tabid/79/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/7421/MONJAYA-IKON-WISATA-BAHARI-JATIM.aspx Monjaya, The Icon of Maritime Tourism {{flagicon|Indonesia}}][[Indonesia|[[File:Flag_of_Indonesia.svg|link=|alt=Indonesia|23x23px]]]][[Indonesia|[[File:Flag_of_Indonesia.svg|link=|alt=Indonesia|23x23px]][[File:Flag_of_Indonesia.svg|link=|alt=Indonesia|23x23px]][[File:Flag_of_Indonesia.svg|link=|alt=Indonesia|23x23px]][[File:Flag_of_Indonesia.svg|link=|alt=Indonesia|23x23px]][[File:Flag_of_Indonesia.svg|link=|alt=Indonesia|23x23px]]]]'', by Indonesian Navy</ref>

