{{Infobox artwork | title = Water, Please | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | wikidata = | image = File:St. Johns Bridge (Multnomah County, Oregon scenic images) (mulDA0062).jpg | image_upright = | alt = | caption = The sculpture in 2010 | artist = Don Merkt | year = {{start date|1997}} | completion_date = <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | catalogue = | medium = | movement = | subject = | height_metric = <!-- (i.e. in metric units) --> | width_metric = | length_metric = | diameter_metric = | height_imperial = <!-- (i.e. in imperial units) --> | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | diameter_imperial = | dimensions = | dimensions_ref = | metric_unit = cm <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | imperial_unit = in <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | weight = | designation = | condition = | museum = | city = [[Portland, Oregon]], United States | coordinates = {{coord|45.58534|N|122.76053|W|type:landmark_region:US-OR|display=inline,title}} | owner = | accession = | preceded_by = <!-- preceding work by the same artist --> | followed_by = <!-- next work by the same artist --> | module = | website = <!-- Official webpage/site only: {{URL|example.com}} --> }} '''''Water, Please''''' is a 1997 aluminum and stainless steel sculpture by Don Merkt, installed outside the Water Pollution Control Laboratory at 6543 North Burlington Avenue, in north [[Portland, Oregon]]'s [[Cathedral Park, Portland, Oregon|Cathedral Park]] neighborhood, in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opb.org/radio/programs/state-of-wonder/article/regional-arts-culture-council-portland-new-leader-search/|title=Portland Regional Arts And Culture Council Looks For New Leadership|last=Baer|first=April|website=www.opb.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-03}}</ref><ref name="PAA">{{cite web |title="Water, Please" |url=http://www.publicartarchive.org/work/water-please |website=Public Art Archive |accessdate=June 3, 2018}}</ref> Inspired by the relationship between people and water, the work is part of the collection of the City of Portland and Multnomah County Public Art Collection courtesy of the [[Regional Arts & Culture Council]].<ref name="CN">{{cite web |title=Water, Please, 1997 |url=http://culturenow.org/entry&permalink=06435&seo=Water-Please_Don-Merkt-and-City-of-Portland-and-Multnomah-County-Public-Art-Collection-courtesy-of-the-Regional-Arts--Culture-Council |website=cultureNOW |accessdate=June 3, 2018}}</ref> It measures 9' x 30' x 54' and was funded by the City of Portland's Bureau of Environmental Services.<ref name="RACC">{{cite web |title=Public Art Search: "Water, Please" |url=https://racc.org/public-art/search/?page=details&skip=202&sort_pref=sort_title&results_per_page=120&search_title=&search_artist=&search_keyword=&search_other=&search_collection=Permanently%20Sited&search_discipline=sculpture&search=Search |publisher=[[Regional Arts & Culture Council]] |accessdate=June 3, 2018}}</ref>
